In Figure 21.1, the value of euros per U.S. dollar is **€ 0.7210**. Hence, we will multiply the $100 to the value of euros per U.S. dollar to determine how many euros we can get.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Euro (€)} &= \text{€ per dollar} \times {{\text{Dollars to exchange in €}}}\\
&= \text{€ 0.7210} \times {{\text{\$100}}}\\
& = \boxed{\text{€ 72.10}}
\end{aligned}$$

In Figure 21.1, the value of euros in U.S. dollar is **$ 1.3869**. Hence, we will multiply the € 5,000,000 to the value of euros in U.S. dollar to determine how many dollars we can get.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{U.S. Dollars (\$)} &= \text{€ in dollar} \times {{\text{Euros to exchange in \$}}}\\
&= \text{\$ 1.3869} \times {{\text{€ 5,000,000}}}\\
& = \boxed{\text{\$ 6,934,500}}
\end{aligned}$$

To determine how many Mexican pesos we can get for a euro, we will multiply the value of the Mexican peso when expressed per U.S dollars and the value of euros when express in U.S dollars.

$$ \begin{aligned}
\text{Mexican Peso (M\$)} &= \text{M\$ per U.S \$} \times {{\text{€ in U.S \$}}}\\
&= \text{M\$ 13.0434} \times {{\text{\$ 1.3869}}}\\
& = \boxed{\text{M\$ 18.0899}}
\end{aligned}$$
